Description:¶

Bigfoot Sightings by State¶

In [2]:
reportsDF = pd.DataFrame(reports)


# There are a lot of null values here, but every report has a STATE and YEAR value.

reports_by_stateDF = reportsDF.groupby(['STATE']).count()

# Dropping columns I don't need for the bar graph

reports_by_stateDF = reports_by_stateDF.drop(['SEASON', 'COUNTY', 'NEAREST_TOWN',
                                             'NEAREST_ROAD', 'OBSERVED', 'ALSO_NOTICED',
                                             'OTHER_WITNESSES', 'OTHER_STORIES', 'TIME_AND_CONDITIONS',
                                             'ENVIRONMENT', 'REPORT_NUMBER', 'REPORT_CLASS', 'LOCATION_DETAILS',
                                             'MONTH', 'DATE', 'A_&_G_References'], axis = 1)
In [3]:
# Using numpy and seaborn here since the instructions asked for examples of these libraries
# (I think it would be more efficient to just work with the DataFrame)

themes.theme_solarized_light2()
plt.rcParams["figure.figsize"] = (15,18)

statesArr = reports_by_stateDF.index.to_numpy()
sightingsArr = reports_by_stateDF.to_numpy()

sightingsArr = sightingsArr.reshape(49,)

newDF = pd.DataFrame(data = [statesArr, sightingsArr]).T
newDF = newDF.sort_values(1, ascending = False) # Sorting by sightings number


barGraph = sns.barplot(x = 1, y = 0, data = newDF, color = 'forestgreen')

barGraph.set_ylabel(ylabel = "STATE", fontsize = 18)
barGraph.set_xlabel(xlabel = "Number of Sightings", fontsize = 18)
barGraph.set_title("Bigfoot Sightings by State\n", fontsize = 23)

Explanation of Code¶

  1. Data read from a json-formatted file (bfro_reports.json)
  2. The data is turned into a Pandas DataFrame
  3. Unneeded columns are dropped from the DataFrame
  4. The data-of-interest is converted into NumPy arrays (to show that I know how to use NumPy arrays)
  5. The NumPy arrays are converted into a DataFrame and sorted
  6. A bar graph is created with Seaborn using the DataFrame

Discussion of Data¶

By far, most Bigfoot sightings recorded in this file occur in the Pacific Northwest. The reports include dates that are pre-internet (two even pre-1990). If someone was to do a more rigorous analysis, I would suggest dropping very old sightings and controlling for state population (this could be difficult due to population growth). That is not to say that "most Bigfoot sightings occur in the Pacific Northwest," but only that "In this file most sightings are reported in the Pacific Northwest."

Data taken from: bfro_reports.json¶

locationsDF = location

print("Unfortunately, the timestamp data is actually in object format:\n")
print(locationsDF.dtypes)
print("\nI tried converting the to the datetime datatype, but there are many years covered by this data.")
print("For that reason, I will only leave the year in the timestamp column and convert that to an integer.\n")

#====================== The 'timestamp' column conversions ====================================================

# Slicing off everything except the year
locationsDF['timestamp'] = locationsDF['timestamp'].str.slice(start = 0, stop = 4)

# Renaming the 'timestamp' column to 'year'
locationsDF = locationsDF.rename(columns = {'timestamp' : 'year'})

# Converting to int
locationsDF['year'] = pd.to_numeric(locationsDF['year'])

#===============================================================================================================

print("The timestamp column is now named \"year\" and has a datatype of int64.\n")
print(locationsDF.dtypes)

plt.style.use("cyberpunk")
plt.rcParams["figure.figsize"] = (20,12) # resizing

# Creating a dataframe of year of sighting, classification of sighting
year_classDF = locationsDF.groupby(['year', 'classification']).size().reset_index(name = 'count')

# There's an entry from 2053 - I'm just going to slice that one off...
year_classDF = year_classDF[:-1]
#year_classDF = year_classDF.set_index('year')

# Making the line green to make it reminiscent of trees
year_classDF.pivot_table('count', index = 'year',aggfunc = 'sum').plot(color = '#00ff41')

plt.tick_params(axis = 'both', labelsize = 15)
plt.xlim(1958, 2021)

plt.ylabel('Number of Sightings', fontsize = 20)
plt.xlabel('Year', fontsize = 20)
plt.title('Reported Bigfoot Sightings (1958 - 2022)', fontsize = 25)
plt.legend(loc = 'upper left', prop = {'size': 20})

mplcyberpunk.make_lines_glow()
mplcyberpunk.add_underglow()

Explanation of Code¶

  1. Data is read from a csv file (bfro_locations.csv) and put into a DataFrame
  2. The data for dates is converted into integer format (where the integer represents the year of the sighting)
  3. A pivot table and aggregate function: sum are used to plot the total sightings reported each year.

Discussion of Data¶

The data contains many sharp rises and falls. It also contains Bigfoot sighting reports from as far back as 1896 to 2053 (yes, really, but I sliced that one off).

The Bigfoot Field Researchers Organization states on their website:

"The BFRO web site was built and launched in 1995. It was the first web site to provide a collection of bigfoot/sasquatch sighting reports. In fact, it was the first web site to provide a database of sighting reports of any type of elusive phenomena. The early success and popularity of the BFRO site led to a minor proliferation of other web sites applying the same formula, to UFO reports, ghost reports, etc.¶

The BFRO site is the only collection of bigfoot reports from across North America that have actually been investigated by researchers to determine credibility. The BFRO has a large network of experienced volunteer investigators across the U.S. and Canada who use various methods to determine the credibility of reports. ... "¶

Source: https://www.bfro.net/gdb/classify.asp¶

This is an interesting bit of history, but I wonder how the volunteer investigators validate a report as far back as 1869 or a report from the future. I've attempted to lessen these concerns by only displaying data from 1958 to 2022. It will also be more clear why I bounded the data between 1958 and 2022 after reading what a "Class C" sighting is in the next section.

Data taken from: bfro_locations.csv¶

What do the classifications mean?¶

From The Bigfoot Field Researchers Organization website:

Class A¶

Class A reports involve clear sightings in circumstances where misinterpretation or misidentification of other animals can be ruled out with greater confidence. For example, there are several footprint cases that are very well documented. These are considered Class A reports, because misidentification of common animals can be confidently ruled out, thus the potential for misinterpretation is very low.¶

Class B¶

Incidents where a possible sasquatch was observed at a great distance or in poor lighting conditions and incidents in any other circumstance that did not afford a clear view of the subject are considered Class B reports. For example, credible reports where nothing was seen but distinct and characteristic sounds of sasquatches were heard are always considered Class B reports and never Class A, even in the most compelling "sound-only" cases. This is because the lack of a visual element raises a much greater potential for a misidentification of the sounds.¶

Class C¶

Most second-hand reports, and any third-hand reports, or stories with an untraceable sources, are considered Class C, because of the high potential for inaccuracy. Those reports are kept in BFRO archives but are very rarely listed publicly in this database. The exceptions are for published, or locally documented incidents from before 1958 (before the word "Bigfoot" entered the American vocabulary), and sightings mentioned in non-tabloid newspapers or magazines.¶

Source: https://www.bfro.net/gdb/classify.asp¶

Explanation of Code¶

  1. A pivot table is used to set "year" as the index and aggfunc: sum is used to sum each classification type
  2. The plot is formatted for readability

Discussion of Data¶

It is interesting that most of the reports are Class A until the mid-2000's where Class B becomes the dominant report type. Is that when people started going into the deep forest less? Did the Sasquatches get better at hiding? Did the 2008 subprime mortgage crisis cause the creatures to be more skeptical of humans?

I don't think I can reasonably draw profound conclusions from this data analysis. All I can say is that Class B becomes the dominant classification after the mid-2000s in the BFRO database.
